<paragraph id="8BBDFC7E7B66D217FF6FFAB1FAB4FA5D" blockId="2.[151,1436,1279,1662]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
This species was described from ‘Zambesi’ (
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B66D217FD62FAB1FC80FAAD" author="Hewitson" box="[666,841,1314,1338]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Hewitson, W. C. (1868) Descriptions of one hundred new species of Hesperidae. John Van Voorst, London, vol. 2, 25 - 56." type="journal article" year="1868">
Hewitson 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FCE8FAB1FC80FAAD" box="[784,841,1314,1338]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1868.0">1868</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and is found from eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FB74FAB0FACEFAAD" box="[1164,1287,1314,1338]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">DR Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FAEFFAB1FEBBFAC9" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Democratic Republic of Congo</collectingCountry>
) to 
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FE5AFAD5FDD3FAC9" box="[418,538,1350,1374]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FDADFAD5FD25FAC9" box="[597,748,1350,1374]" name="Mozambique" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
, northwards to 
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FC58FAD4FC20FAC8" box="[928,1001,1351,1375]" name="Kenya" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Kenya</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B66D217FC02FAD5FB58FAC9" author="Evans" box="[1018,1169,1350,1374]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Evans, W. H. (1937 a) A catalogue of the African Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, UK, 212 pp, 30 plates." type="book" year="1937" yearSuffix="a">
Evans 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FBB1FAD5FB4AFAC9" box="[1097,1155,1350,1374]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1937.0">1937</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B66D217FB66FAD5FA8AFAC9" author="Kielland" box="[1182,1347,1350,1374]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Kielland, J. (1990) Butterflies of Tanzania. Hill House, Melbourne, Australia, 363 pp." type="book" year="1990">
Kielland 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FAF0FAD5FA8AFAC9" box="[1288,1347,1350,1374]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1990.0">1990</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B66D217FAA8FAD4FF1AFA15" author="Larsen" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Larsen, T. B. (1991) The Butterflies of Kenya and their Natural History. Oxford University Press, Oxford, UK, 490 pp." type="book" year="1991">
Larsen 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FF6FFAF9FF1AFA15" box="[151,211,1386,1410]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FEF3FAF9FEBAFA15" box="[267,371,1386,1410]" name="Tanzania" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, ssp. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B66D217FE48FAFFFDC5FA14" box="[432,524,1388,1411]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Ampittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="capenas">
<emphasis id="B976206C7B66D217FE48FAFFFDC5FA14" box="[432,524,1388,1411]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">capenas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F315BCEE7B66D217FD1FFAF9FC86FA15" box="[743,847,1386,1410]" name="Tanzania" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, while ssp. 
<emphasis id="B976206C7B66D217FC29FAF8FBD6FA14" box="[977,1055,1387,1411]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">blanda</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF93818F7B66D217FBDDFAF8FB72FA15" author="Evans" box="[1061,1211,1386,1410]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Evans, W. H. (1947) Revisional notes on African Hesperiidae. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 11, 13, 641 - 648." type="journal article" year="1947">
Evans (
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FB81FAF9FB7DFA15" box="[1145,1204,1386,1410]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1947.0">1947</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
is in the west. This is a woodland species but is also found in more open formations and forest margins. 
<collectionCode id="ED1364BB7B66D217FBB6FA1DFB5CFA31" box="[1102,1173,1422,1446]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">TCEC</collectionCode>
found the food plant to be an unidentified grass (
<taxonomicName id="4C0287FD7B66D217FE48FA21FDC6FA5D" box="[432,527,1458,1482]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
)—this appears to be the first confirmed record of a food plant for this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBDFC7E7B66D217FF3FFA45FE2BF9E9" blockId="2.[151,1436,1279,1662]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The leaf shelter of the mature caterpillar is made by rolling a leaf upwards, and tying it with silk strands, with feeding distal to this leaving the mid-rib bared (
<figureCitation id="1339E0FB7B66D217FD48FA69FCC6F985" box="[688,783,1530,1554]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1976,1999]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1714,1959]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1714,1960]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Leaf shelter of final instar caterpillar of Ampittia capenas on unidentified grass, Rondo Plateau, SE Tanzania, 850 m, 0 9 Feb 2005, TCEC." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246332/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figure 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FCFAFA69FCC6F985" box="[770,783,1530,1554]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). The mature caterpillar is pale green with a black dorsal plate T 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FF15F98DFF31F9A1" box="[237,248,1566,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1.0">1</number>
, and a black, rugose head (
<figureCitation id="1339E0FB7B66D217FDC3F98DFD68F9A1" box="[571,673,1566,1590]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,520,543]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,153,498]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,153,498]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Final instar caterpillar of Ampittia capenas on unidentified grass, Rondo Plateau, SE Tanzania, 850 m, 0 9 Feb 2005, TCEC. 1, dorsal view; 2, head anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246333/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figure 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FD68F98DFD68F9A1" box="[656,673,1566,1590]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). The pupa is cylindrical, white and has two anterior projections angled outwards at right angles to the body (
<figureCitation id="1339E0FB7B66D217FD68F9D1FD3AF9CD" box="[656,755,1602,1626]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1541,1564]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,653,1519]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,653,1520]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pupa of Ampittia capenas collected on unidentified grass, Rondo Plateau, SE Tanzania, 850 m, 0 9 Feb 2005, photographed 13 Feb 2005, TCEC. 1, dorsal view; 2, lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/246334/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figure 
<number id="3DCAEE597B66D217FD1BF9D1FD3AF9CD" box="[739,755,1602,1626]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). It is formed in a completely closed grass leaf tube shelter and attached at the cremaster.
</paragraph>
